player.seasonOutlook: As the old saying goes "the best ability, is availability," and no NHL goaltender was more available than Saros last season. He led the league in appearances with 64 and finished tied for sixth in wins with 35. That's the good news. The bad news is that Saros' 2.86 GAA and .906 save percentage were the worst marks of his career. That's simply something fantasy managers will have to live with when you consider how many games Saros plays for a middling Nashville team. The long-term status of the Finn was secured with an eight-year contract extension in July, making him a clear-cut No. 1 goalie with the potential for a bounce-back campaign if the Predators' offseason upgrades lead to better performances on the ice.

Grubauer has been remarkably consistent for Seattle the past two seasons, although not in a positive way. His numbers from a year ago - 14-16-2, 2.85 GAA, .899 save percentage - were nearly identical to the 2022-23 campaign. The Kraken struggled as a team for a second straight season and Grubauer was unable to bail them out. Set to turn 33 this coming November, Grubauer is probably going to be the starter for Seattle come the fall, but that's only because he has three years left on his contract at a cap hit of $5.9 million. His 49-61-11 mark in three seasons with the team suggests you can do better on draft day.

There's a case to be made that no player in the NHL is as important to his team as Shesterkin is to the Rangers. He had his ups and downs throughout the regular season, but still finished with 36 wins along with a 2.58 GAA and a .912 save percentage. If that's your "down" year, you're in pretty good shape. Shesterkin dragged the Rangers to the Eastern Conference Finals almost singlehandedly before being finished off by Florida in six games. Shesterkin appeared in 55 regular-season games, while veteran Jonathan Quick handled the rest. It made for a nice partnership and it's one that will continue for the 2024-25 campaign. Shesterkin is right there with Winnipeg's Connor Hellebuyck as top goaltending options from a fantasy standpoint for the upcoming year.

A year removed from appearing in just 32 games for Vancouver, Demko was again bit by the injury bug in 2023-24. The good news is that he was exceptional when healthy, posting a 35-14-2 record, a 2.45 GAA, a .918 save percentage and five shutouts while being named a finalist for the Vezina Trophy. A knee issue resulted in him missing the final month of the regular season before he aggravated the ailment in the postseason. Demko was believed to be close to returning at the time Vancouver was eliminated by Edmonton in Game 7 of the Western Conference Semifinals, something that bodes well for his availability at the start of the 2024-25 campaign. Demko is a locked-in No. 1 fantasy netminder for this coming season, but just keep in mind he's a greater injury risk than most of the other top-tier guys at the position.

Andersen missed most of last season due to a blood clotting issue. He finally returned in March and the Hurricanes were very careful about his usage, never playing him in back-to-back games. He was brilliant in 16 appearances, going 13-2-0 with a 1.84 GAA and .932 save percentage. Andersen took over as Carolina's full-time starter in the playoffs and was up and down, posting a 2.62 GAA and .895 save percentage in ten games. Andersen always plays well when healthy, but he's one of the bigger injury risks in the league among goaltenders. Toss in the fact the Hurricanes have an excellent backup in youngster Pyotr Kochetkov and Andersen becomes a risky fantasy pick despite the fact he plays for one of the best teams in the NHL.

Another of the countless goaltenders around the league to miss significant time last season, Hill appeared in just 35 regular-season games. He went 19-12-2 with a 2.71 GAA, a .909 save percentage and a pair of shutouts. Hill appeared destined for a timeshare once again in 2024-25, but then the Golden Knights shockingly went out and dealt Logan Thompson to Washington. That moves Hill into the unquestioned No. 1 role, with Ilya Samsonov signed to a one-year deal to serve as the backup. Hill is a serious health risk, but also has a ton of fantasy upside as the unquestioned starter on what projects to be one of the NHL's best teams.

The Capitals were one of the worst teams in recent memory to secure a playoff spot a year ago, but they did indeed make it, and Lindgren was the most significant reason why. The career journeyman ripped the No. 1 job away from overpriced veteran Darcy Kuemper and proceeded to post a 25-16-7 record, a 2.67 GAA and a .911 save percentage in 50 appearances. At 30 years old and with no sustained history of playing at a high level, Lindgren seems like a poor bet to repeat his numbers in 2024-25. Washington clearly agreed to some extent, going out and trading for Logan Thompson from Vegas instead of signing a cheap veteran backup. This has all the makings of a timeshare, similar to what Thompson endured the last several seasons with the Golden Knights.

Available at a massive discount in drafts a year ago, Binnington quietly put together a solid fantasy season. He won 28 games for the Blues, his most since 2019-20. His 2.84 GAA and .913 save percentage were considerably better than the type of numbers we saw from him in recent years. It's difficult to see Binnington taking an additional step forward given the fact he plays for a middling St. Louis club, but with three more years on his contract at a cap hit of $6 million and with only youngster Joel Hofer behind him on the depth chart, Binnington is again shaping up as a reasonable No. 2 fantasy goaltender for the 2024-25 campaign.

Samsonov signed a one-year, $1.8 million contract with Vegas in the summer following a tumultuous 2023-24 campaign for Toronto. He posted a 5-2-6 record with an .862 save percentage before landing on waivers and being sent to the AHL. Although Samsonov didn't see any playing time in the minors, it was a beneficial wake-up call, and his break from the roster helped him get back on track. After returning to the Maple Leafs, he went 18-5-2 with two shutouts and a .904 save percentage. However, his 3.13 GAA and .890 save percentage in 40 appearances was a significant step backward from his 2.33 GAA and .919 save percentage over 42 contests in 2022-23. As a member of the Golden Knights, he will serve as Adin Hill's backup. If Hill struggles with injuries again, Samsonov could provide solid fantasy value, especially as a spot starter.

There's most definitely a case to be made that Hellebuyck was the most valuable fantasy goaltender in the league a season ago. He finished second in the NHL with 37 wins and posted excellent marks in both GAA (2.39) and save percentage (.921). His 60 appearances trailed only Colorado's Alexandar Georgiev and Nashville's Juuse Saros. A four-time finalist (including each of the past two years) for the Vezina Trophy as the best goaltender in the NHL, Hellebuyck - who signed a new seven-year, $59.5 million deal just days before the start of last season - is an odds-on favorite to be one of the first two goaltenders off the board in fantasy drafts this coming season.

Vasilevskiy has been arguably the best goaltender in the NHL for well over a half-decade now, but he, along with his team in Tampa Bay, appears to be trending in the wrong direction. His season got off to a late start following offseason back surgery, but Vasilevskiy still managed to post 30-plus wins (30) for the seventh straight year. That's the good news. The bad news is that his GAA (2.90) and save percentage (.900) were the worst marks of his decade-long NHL career. Vasilevskiy remains a No. 1 fantasy goaltender, but the days of the 30-year-old Russian being the no-doubt best option at the position could come to a close soon.

Oettinger had a strange season. His 35 victories placed him tied for sixth in the NHL, but his 2.72 GAA and .905 save percentage were both the worst marks of his career by a wide margin. The main reason for the struggles were the fact Oettinger allowed at least five goals on seven separate occasions, stunning numbers for one of the better goalies in the league who also plays on one of best teams. The fact Oettinger missed the better part of a month beginning in mid-December with a lower-body issue didn't help matters. If the Boston University product can eliminate a handful of those stinkers in 2024-25, his overall numbers should rebound. Oettinger is a No. 1 fantasy goaltender in all formats based on the win totals alone.

Playing for arguably the best team in the NHL, Bobrovsky had his best season in half a decade. He won 30-plus games (36) for the seventh time in his career, to go along with a sparkling 2.37 GAA and .915 save percentage. He was also fantastic in leading the Panthers to the Stanley Cup. Set to play the entirety of this upcoming season at age 36, Bobrovsky is getting up there in age. That said, he remains the unquestioned starter for one of the league's premier teams, once again making him a low-end No. 1 fantasy option for the 2024-25 campaign.

Gustavsson was viewed as a popular breakout fantasy candidate a year ago, but the Swede stumbled to a 20-17-5 record, a 3.06 GAA and an .899 save percentage in 45 appearances. The numbers were shocking given Gustavsson's 2.10 GAA and .931 save percentage a year prior. Clearly not comfortable with the direction in which Gustavsson is trending, the Wild brought back 39-year-old Marc-Andre Fleury for what will be his 20th and final NHL season. The two are almost certainly looking at a timeshare of some sort unless Gustavsson unexpectedly regains his form of two years ago.

Once again splitting time with Linus Ullmark a season ago, Swayman appeared in 44 games for Boston. He picked up a career-high 25 wins, to go along with a 2.53 GAA, a .916 save percentage and three shutouts. Seeking to commit to just one option moving forward, the Bruins dealt Ullmark to Ottawa in late June. That opens the door for the 25-year-old Swayman to serve as Boston's unquestioned No. 1 goaltender for the first time in his four-year NHL career. From a fantasy standpoint, Swayman may not be on that same level as top-tier options such as Connor Hellebuyck and Igor Shesterkin, but he isn't far off. The Alaska native projects as a front-line fantasy starter in all formats this coming year.

Drafted as a top goaltending option in fantasy leagues a year ago, Sorokin burned anyone that was willing to grab him that early. Playing for a thoroughly mediocre Islanders team, Sorokin finished with 25 wins, along with a 3.01 GAA and .908 save percentage. This on the heels of a year in which he posted 31 wins, a 2.34 GAA and a .924 save percentage. Things got so bad that he was benched for veteran Semyon Varlamov for most of the Islanders' late-season push and nearly their entire brief playoff run. Sorokin is signed through 2031-32 at a cap hit of $8.25 million, so there's no easy fix forthcoming. Sorokin is a theoretical bounce-back candidate based on pure talent alone, but there's nothing to suggest the Islanders are going to take a step forward as a team in 2024-25.

A .500 record (23-23-2), a 2.78 GAA and a .905 save percentage don't seem like anything to write home about, but Markstrom was the only player on the Calgary roster that showed up most nights a season ago. He played well in what was quickly developing into a dysfunctional situation. The Flames and Devils had trade talks about Markstrom during the season but couldn't close a deal. They finally agreed to terms in June, with the Swedish netminder waving his full no-move clause to switch teams. Markstrom should help solve New Jersey's goaltending woes, making him a low-end No. 1 fantasy netminder for the 2024-25 campaign.

Ullmark's brilliant three-year run in Boston came to an end following a trade to Ottawa in late June. Last season might have been his worst of the three and he still managed to go 22-10-7 with a 2.58 GAA and a .915 save percentage. The move has positives and negatives from a fantasy standpoint. Ullmark will be the unquestioned starter for the Senators, getting as much playing time as he can handle, but he's also joining a significantly worse team, especially on the defensive side. Ullmark didn't fare all that well under similar circumstances early in his career in Buffalo. He's still a worthy low-end No. 1 fantasy netminder, but don't pay for past production.

Georgiev led the NHL in wins in 2023-24 with 38, and thankfully so, because the rest of his numbers took a massive nosedive. His 63 appearances were one behind Nashville's Juuse Saros for most in the league, but his 3.02 GAA and .897 save percentage were both a massive disappointment given the 2.53 GAA and .918 save percentage he posted a year prior. Georgiev lost playing time to backup Justus Annunen late in the year before regaining the net for the club's postseason run. Set to hit unrestricted free agency in the summer of 2025, Georgiev is likely to open the 2024-25 campaign as Colorado's starter, but a slow start to the season could quickly lead to an increased role for Annunen.

Talbot got off to a roaring start with the Kings a season ago but cratered late in the year and in the playoffs. All told, Talbot won 27 regular-season games to go along with a 2.50 GAA and .913 save percentage. With nominal starter Ville Husso constantly injured and fellow veteran Alex Lyon best served in a backup role, Detroit inked Talbot to a two-year, $5 million contract on July 1. Talbot should have a chance for playing time with a team that is theoretically on the rise, but this has all the makings of a full-blown committee in net, and potentially a three-man timeshare rather than a more palatable 50-50 situation.

Skinner was a workhorse for the Oilers last season, appearing in 59 games for the club. That placed him fourth in the NHL behind only Juuse Saros, Alexandar Georgiev and Connor Hellebuyck. Skinner had his fair share of stinkers, but his overall numbers - 36-16-5, 2.62 GAA, .905 save percentage - were perfectly acceptable. It's worth noting that most of the Skinner's fantasy value is tied to playing time and the fact he is part of a team that has the likes of Connor McDavid and Leon Draisaitl on it. Things can change in an instant in this sport, but fresh off a season in which he led Edmonton to the Stanley Cup Finals, Skinner should be safe to select as a low-end No. 1 fantasy netminder for 2024-25.

Woll was banged up most of last year, ending up sidelined a good portion of both the regular season and during Toronto's brief playoff run. He appeared in just 25 of 82 regular-season games, going 12-11-1 with a 2.93 GAA and a .907 save percentage. Clearly not deterred, the Maple Leafs inked Woll to a three-year extension worth a shade under $11 million when he became eligible July 1. They then brought in respected veteran Anthony Stolarz to serve as the backup. Woll is going to open the 2024-25 campaign as Toronto's starter and should have a good bit of fantasy value if he's healthy, but the latter is far from a guarantee given what we saw this past season.

The Sabres began last season with youngster Devon Levi as their starter, but he struggled, allowing Luukkonen to seize the No. 1 job in late October and hold it the remainder of the year. All told, UPL appeared in 54 games, going 27-22-4 with a 2.57 GAA, a .910 save percentage and five shutouts. They were perfectly competent numbers from a guy who turned 25 in March. Luukkonen is once again positioned to be the top goalie for Buffalo, with Levi and veteran James Reimer battling for backup duties. UPL is best projected as a high-end No. 2 netminder from a fantasy standpoint.

Wolf made his season debut for the Flames in November and saw sporadic playing time, mostly late in the year. He appeared in 17 games in total, going 7-7-1 with a 3.15 GAA and an .893 save percentage. The numbers look underwhelming, but Wolf will play nearly the entirety of this upcoming season at age 23 and he has been the unquestioned top goaltender in the AHL over the past several years. With Jacob Markstorm traded to New Jersey, Wolf will battle veteran Dan Vladar for playing time. The latter is nothing but a short-term stopgap option, so Wolf should be considered the favorite for starts.

Ingram surprisingly earned most of the playing time in net for the then-Coyotes last season, appearing in 50 of 82 regular-season games. His 23-21-1 record was mediocre, as was his 2.91 GAA and .907 save percentage, but Ingram did post six shutouts, tied for most in the NHL. That said, nothing in Ingram's background suggests he is ready to be a No. 1 starter at this level and Utah has a perfectly capable 1B option in Karel Vejmelka. This has all the makings of a timeshare on what projects to be a poor defensive team. That's a fantasy situation to avoid.

The Canadiens carried three goalies on their roster much of last year, a move that didn't help any of the netminders involved. Montembeault got the most playing time of the group, appearing in 41 games and going 16-15-9 with a 3.14 GAA and a .903 save percentage. Montembeault had plenty of excellent efforts, but also had his fair share of stinkers, something which will continue to happen playing behind a well below-average defensive team. Montembeault is in line to open the year once again as Montreal's starter, but backup Cayden Primeau will push for playing time, making neither a particularly attractive fantasy option on a middling club.

Signed to a five-year contract worth a shade under $27 million last July, Jarry proceeded to have the worst season of his career before losing his starting job to Alex Nedeljkovic as the Penguins made a late push towards the playoffs. Jarry's 2.91 GAA and .903 save percentage were in line with what we saw from him two seasons ago, but the 19-25-5 record was brutal. His six shutouts tied for the league lead, but he allowed five or more goals on five separate occasions. The biggest concern of all is the fact Jarry made just one relief appearance over Pittsburgh's final 12 regular-season games. Nedeljkovic signed a two-year contract in June, but Jarry's contract suggests he's in line to return as the starter for the Pens. It's impossible to have any confidence in Jarry from a fantasy standpoint after how last season ended.

With former No. 1 goaltender Carter Hart placed on leave in January due to legal reasons, Ersson took over as the starter for the Flyers the rest of the way. He appeared in 51 games, going 23-19-7 with a 2.82 GAA and an .890 save percentage. Ersson was notably ineffective late in the season, at which point head coach John Tortorella openly admitted they were forced to play him more than they had hoped. Ersson's top contender for playing time this coming season will be KHL import Ivan Fedotov, who joined the team late last season and signed a two-year deal in late April to avoid free agency. This has the makings of a full-blown timeshare, leaving neither goalie with much fantasy value on a middling club.

Having lost his starting job to Charlie Lindgren in Washington, Kuemper was traded to Los Angeles in June straight up for Pierre-Luc Dubois in a deal involving struggling, high-priced veterans. Kuemper appeared in 33 games for the Capitals a season ago, posting a woeful 13-14-3 record, a 3.31 GAA and an .890 save percentage. The move to the Kings could theoretically do wonders for Kuemper's fantasy value if he is able to beat out journeyman David Rittich for playing time. With three years left on a contract that pays him $5.25 million annually, Los Angeles is undoubtedly hoping Kuemper regains the form which made him one of the better goaltenders in the NHL not all that long ago.

A 32-year-old, oft-injured veteran, Mrazek appeared in a career-high 56 games a season ago for Chicago and played quite well, all things considered. His GAA (3.04) and save percentage (.907) numbers were his best in three seasons, and the fact he managed to pick up 18 wins (18-31-4) while playing for one of the least talented teams in the NHL was impressive. He was certainly an upgrade over backup Arvid Soderblom, who appeared in 32 games a year ago and posted a mind-numbing 5-22-2 mark, though the Blackhawks signed Laurent Brossoit to fill that role in 2024-25. Mrazek is far from a lock to make it through this coming season in one piece, but he's a reasonable late-round option for any fantasy managers looking for a starting goalie.

Gibson's name has been popping up in trade rumors for years, but he's yet to be dealt. As a result, he's still with the Ducks, seemingly constantly dealing with nagging injuries and not playing well when healthy behind a poor team. Gibson went 13-27-2 a season ago along with a 3.54 GAA and an .888 save percentage. The latter number was by far the worst of his career and for now, there's no real reason to expect things to improve. Gibson isn't without talent, but it's become quite clear at this point he needs a move out of Anaheim to salvage any semblance of fantasy value moving forward.

Blackwood's first season in San Jose was predictably a disaster, which is almost always the case for any goaltender playing behind the worst team in the league. He was often banged up and entirely ineffective when healthy, finishing with a 10-25-4 record, 3.45 GAA and .899 save percentage. Blackwood hasn't had a GAA under 3.00 since 2019-20 or a save percentage over .900 since 2021-22, so it's not as if he was playing well in New Jersey prior to the move to the Sharks. Signed for one more season at $2.35 million, Blackwood should open the 2024-25 campaign as San Jose's starter but isn't an option in any format given his own play and the quality, or lack thereof, of talent around him.

Merzlikins went 13-17-8 for the Jackets a season ago, with a 3.45 GAA and an .897 save percentage. The numbers, while dreadful, were all a considerable improvement from a year prior. With the team going nowhere and his play deteriorating, Merzlikins confirmed he requested a trade in January. Unsurprisingly, no one had interest in dealing for a struggling netminder with three years left on his contract at a cap hit of $5.4 million. There's no easy fix here. Assuming he isn't dealt, the 30-year-old will probably begin the year as Columbus' starter, but his fantasy value will be minimal playing for arguably the most dysfunctional organization in the NHL.

Vanecek was excellent in 2022-23, posting a 33-11-4 record with a 2.45 GAA and a .911 save percentage in 52 appearances with New Jersey. Despite posting a solid mark of 17-9-3 last season, he struggled with a 3.18 GAA and an .890 save percentage in 32 contests. The Devils dealt him to San Jose in March, but he didn't see any game action because of injury. However, Vanecek is expected to be ready for training camp. He will compete with Mackenzie Blackwood, another crease casualty of New Jersey, for playing time in 2024-25. It will be challenging for whoever starts for the rebuilding Sharks to keep pucks out of the net, so taking a wait-and-see approach with Vanecek and Blackwood is recommended.
